{"/service/ndnp/dlc/batch_dlc_2abbott_ver01/data/sn83045462/00280604604/1945101401/0615.xml":{"full_text":"w Sunday flfat4\nVFiik Daily Evening i.dition.\nTHEODORE W. NOYES, Editor.\nWASHING! ON, D. C.\nThe Evening Star Newspaper Company\nMain Cfflce: 11th St. and Pennsylvania Ave.\nNew York Office: 110 Bast 4:M St.\nChicago Office: 435 North Michigan Ave%\nDelivered by Carrier\u2014Metropolitan Area\nEffective October 1, 1044.\nRegular Edition. 4 Sundays. 3 Sundays.\nEvening and Sunday 90c per mo. *1 .00 per mo\nThe Evening Star _ 60c per month.\nThe Sunday Star 10c per copy.\nNight Final Edition. 4 Sundays 5 Sundays\nNight Final and Sunday $1.00 mo. *1.10 mo\nNight Final Star 75c par month.\nRate* by Mail\u2014Payable in Advance.\nAnywhere in United States.\n_ 1 month. 6 months. 1 year\nEvening and Sunday $1.00 $6.00 $l\u201d.0(\nThe Evening Star .75 4 00 s OC\nThe Sunday Star .50 2.50 5.0t\nTelephone National 5000.\nEntered at the Post Office. Washington. D. C.,\nas second-class mall matter.\nMember of the Associated Press.\nThe Associated Press Is exclusively entitled to\nthe use for repablication of all news dispatches\ncredited to U or not otherwise credited in this\n^,Ber VI*5 *I\u2018\u00b0 local news published herein.\nAll rights of publication of special dispatches\nherein also are reserved.\nC\u20142 SUNDAY, October 14, 1945\nEisenhower on Germany\nGeneral Eisenhower's emphatic\nremarks on our policy in Germany\nare timely and to the point. For\nsome weeks past there have been\nnumerous reports of a tendency\namong some American occupation\nauthorities to be half-hearted about\ndoing the job that must be done if\nNaziism and Prussian militarism are\nto be extirpated. Indeed, the sus\npicion has been expressed that cer\ntain groups favor the idea of let\nting the defeated Reich recover its\nstrength in order to help build a\nwestern bloc against Russia.\nAs evidence of the latter, critics\nof our occupation policy have cited\nthe fact that in a report submitted\nto the Army, American economic ex\nperts have advocated a program of\nindustrial demilitarization less dras\ntic for Germany than that called for\nin the Potsdam agreement. The\nmain point of this report is that\nsome modifications are necessary if\nthe German people are to be able to\nbuild a self-supporting peacetime\neconomy. This is a highly debatable\nmatter, of course, but in any case\nboth General Eisenhower and his\ndeputy. General Clay, now have\nmade clear that the report itself was\ndrawn up merely as a \u201cdiscussion\npiece,\u201d that it has not been accepted\nas policy, that the Potsdam terms\nstill stand as the controlling direc\ntive in any conflict of ideas, and that\nconclusion-jumping to the contrary\nis entirely unwarranted.\nGeneral Eisenhower does not\nmince wrords in answering those who\nhave been questioning the good\nfaith of the Army in this respect.\nErrors have been made by our mili\ntary government, he says, but we\ncan be sure that Naziism is to be\nuprooted \u201cin every shape and form\u201d\nand that officers who are lax in this\nwill be relieved of their jobs. Mis\ntakes here and there, he advises,\nought not to be magnified beyond\ntheir true proportions, because it is\nthe over-all job that counts. As for\nhimself, his determination to see to\nit that that job is well done may be\nsummed up best in his own words:\n\u201cWe got our orders from Potsdam,\nand they are right down my alley.\nI say let Germany find out what it\nmeans to start war.\u201d\nConceiV-ably, the Allied occupying\nauthorities may in time find it wise\nto modify some of the Potsdam eco\nnomic terms, but, as far as General\nEisenhower is concerned\u2014and he\nspeaks and acts for our Govern\nment\u2014there will be no undermining\nof the basic twofold objective of the\noccupation: (1) To insure that Ger\nmany will never again be able to\nmenace Europe and the world, and\n(2) to*\u201cgive the Germans a chance\nto dig themselves out of the gutter\u201d\nand become a nation worthy of in\nternational trust. This should re\nassure all those who have been fear\nful of a \u201csoft\u201d American policy.\nShelling Corn\nThere are plenty of ways for a\nlad to spend a rainy Saturday in the\nfall besides shelling corn. A fellow\ncan always put on some old clothes\nand explore the woodlot and the\nbrook banks in the slough for likely\nspots to set his traps. He could, if\nallowed to follow his inclination,\npore over the mail order catalog. A\nfellow usually has a good book to\nread, something like the \u201cLife of a\nLonely Trapper in the Northland.\u201d\nOr perhaps he had been planning\non finishing that bow and arrow set.\nBut no, at breakfast on a stormy\nSaturday morning father was almost\nsure to say, \u201cWell, son, I guess you\u2019d\nbetter shell corn today. We\u2019ll need\nsome soon for the hogs.\u201d\nAfter one got going it was not too\nbad a job. A fair-minded lad was\nquick to acknowledge it was in\nfinitely preferable to cleaning out\nthe henhouse or shoveling the saw\ndust from the old icehouse. First\none brought several bushels of corn\nears from the crib. Then he started\nup the gasoline engine, slipped the\nsmooth, worn belt over the pulley\nwheel and began feeding the ears\none at a time into the gears that\nripped the kernels from the cobs.\nThere was something almost\nfascinating about the process as the\nears went in and the golden kernels\ndribbled out the spout into old, bat\ntered tin baskets. There was the\nrhythmic, staccato chug-chug of the\nengine. As one hand pushed a long\ncob into the opening and the iron\nteeth grabbed at and pulled it\nthrough, the other hand was reach\ning for the next ear. It was pecu\nliarly satisfying work, for one knew\nhe was providing good food for the\nfarm\u2019s livestock, and those who live\nclose to the soil are conscious of the\nfundamental value of food.\nHowever, an hour or so after din\nner, when one was wondering\nwhether he would ever get enough\ncorn shelled, it was a happy moment\nWhen father happened by and said\ncasually: \u201cWell, son, I guess that\u2019s\nenough for this time. Can you find\nsomething to do for yourself for the\nrest of the day?\u201d\nTrifling With Victory\nWhen Adoll Hitler sent his armies\nstorming into Poland in 1939 this\ncountry, in the words of General\nMarshall, wa$ not even a third-rate\nmilitary power so far as its available\nstrength was concerned. We were\nso weak that Hitler ignored us in\nhis calculations, and although the\nwar has been won because we were\nlucky and because time was pur\nchased for us with the blood of our\nAllies, it is painful to think of the\nlives that have been sacrificed and\nthe hundreds of billions of dollars\nthat have been thrown away be\ncause, in advance of war, we refused\nto make the relatively minor prep\narations that might have prevented\nthe conflict and which certainly\ni would have minimized its destruc\ntive consequences.\nIn 1939 most of us simply refused\n1 to believe that the United States\nwould have to fight a war. We were\n1 utterly and wdllfully blind to the\nI truth. We were concerned with pre\nserving our social gains and, even a\nyear later, we were still talking non\ni sensically about superimposing a\nI defense program on our normal in\ndustrial operations. Yet we had\nmade progress when w'ar came on\nDecember 7, 1941, and while still\nwoefully weak in the military sense,\nthe unfaltering courage of the Brit\nish and the Russians gave us the\nadditional time needed to mobilize\nour potential strength, to become\nI the greatest military power in the\nwTorld. It was a costly process, cost\nI ly in lives and costly in resources,\nbut it should have demonstrated\nonce and for all the folly of national\nweakness. Apparently, however, that\nlesson has not been learned.\nAll of our energies at this time are\nbeing devoted to the tearing down\nof our military organization, and the\ni public is demanding that this be\ndone with even greater speed. The\nproposal for universal military train\ning, which General Marshall so\nearnestly advocates as the only feas\nible means of insuring our future se\ncurity, cannot gain an attentive,\nmuch less a sympathetic, audience.\nIn a word, we are reverting with\nreckless haste to a status of relative\nmilitary weakness. No one can esti\nmate how far this process will be\npermitted to go, but we may be cer\ntain that the other powers are\nwatching us closely and that our in\nfluence throughout the world will\ndiminish as our military power de\ncreases.\nTo offset the inevitable loss in ac\ntual military power, inevitable be\ncause this country would never foot\nthe bill for a large professional mil\nitary establishment even if that were\nj desirable in our system, General\nI Marshall and virtually all of his as\nsociates have pleaded for adoption of\na system of universal military train\ning\u2014not service\u2014as the single alter\nnative which would enable this coun\ntry to be an influential factor in\nmaintaining peace and to defend it\nself in event of attack. The choice,\ni in The Star\u2019s opinion, is very clear.\nEither we will lapse back into a state\nof military weakness and thereby\nthrow away the hope of security and\nfreedom for which this war was\nfought, or we will build up the re\nserve of strength which can come\nonly through universal training and\nthereby serve notice on the world\nthat we intend to be a real factor in\nthe maintenance of peace and a Na\ntion capable of defending itself if\nattacked.\nSome years ago, when the military\nweakness of the western nations\nthreatened them with final ruin at\nthe hands of the Axis, General Mac\nArthur wrote these words: The his\ntory of failure in war can almost be\nsummed up in two words: Too late\ntoo late in comprehending the\ndeadly purpose of a potential en\nemy; too late in realizing the mortal\ndanger; too late in preparedness;\ntoo late in uniting all possible forces\nfor resistance: too late in standing\nwith one's friends.\u201d\nThis time, thanks to our coura\ngeous friends, we in the United States\nwere' almost, but not quite, too late.\nBut if there should be another war\nthere will be no friends in a position\nto buy us two or three years of time.\nIf we are too late in organizing our\nown defenses we will then learn what\nit means to lose a total war.\nOutlook in China\nAfter negotiating for 45 days, the\ncentral government of Generalis\nsimo Chiang Kai-shek and the Chi\nnese Communists headed by Mao\nTze-tung have failed to agree on\nthe basic question of administrative\nand military unity, but they have\nreached a limited accord holding\nout considerable hope for the future.\nIn Mao\u2019s opinion\u2014given as he left\nChungking for his Yenan headquar\nters\u2014there is reason to be optimis\ntic, and the communique issued\njointly by himself and Chiang at\nleast indicated a marked improve\nment in the once-tense situation.\nThe first point in the limited ac\ncord is that both parties commit\nthemselves to the objective of avoid\ning civil war and building a free and\nprosperous China. To this end,\nChiang\u2019s government now stands\nobligated to release political pris\noners, encourage local autonomy,\nannul laws prohibiting freedom of\nperson, conscience, speech, press and\nassembly; recognize that all political\nparties are equal before the law, and\nform a \u201cconsultative council\u201d made\nup of representatives of those parties\n\u2014principally Mao\u2019s group\u2014to plan\nfor a national congress to end the\none-party rule of Chiang\u2019s Kuomin\ntang.\nIf these conditions are met\u2014par\nticularly the condition of avoiding\ncivil war\u2014the complex problem of\na\nadministrative and military unity\nwill become much more manageable.\nThe Chinese Communists would like\nto have the right to name the gov\nernors for the provinces of North\nChina, but Chiang\u2019s government Is\nflatly opposed to this. Similarly, dif\nferences continue over the issue of\nhow the large Communist armed\nforces are to be handled when and\nif China really becomes united. These\nare thorny questions, but the limited\naccord provides that the projected\n\u201cconsultative council\u201d and a special\nmilitary committee will continue to\nwork on them in an effort to attain\na final settlement.\nAs matters stand today, Chiang\u2019s\nbargaining position seems to be\nstronger than that of the Commu\nnists for two reasons: First, because\nRussia, in its new thirty-year treaty\nwith China, has committed Itself to\nsupport his government both morally\nand materially, and second, because\nhe continues to have the full back\ning of the United States, as evi\ndenced by the fact that the Ameri\nj can Tenth Air Force is now engaged\nin flying two of his armies into the\nj northern provinces. This air-borne\nmovement has led some observers to\nfear the possibility of bloody clashes,\nbut Mao who must have been\naware of it when he made his opti\nmistic statement has shown no\nsigns of being disturbed by it. All\nthings considered, although there\nare many serious difficulties to be\nsurmounted, the outlook in China\nseems more encouraging than it has\nbeen in a long time.\nBritish Labor Paraiiel\nThere is a \u201cstriking\" parallel in\nthe literal as well as the figurative\nsense between our own postwar labor\ntroubles and those developing in\nBritain. In both countries the root\ncause is the same. Organized labor\nseeks to retain its wartime wage\nlevel by demanding regular wage in\ncreases sufficient to make up for\nlosses in overtime pay which are\nceasing as the war emergency gives\nplace to peacetime conditions where\nin overtime is economically needless.\nThose demands are coupled with\nwidespread use of the strike weapon,\nregardless of its effect upon recon\nversion, price-levels and inflation\nary possibilities. Indeed, some of\nthe most damaging walkouts are\n\u201cwildcat\u201d strikes undertaken by the\nrank-and-file against the orders and\nin open defiance of their union lead\ners. The outstanding instance of this\ntrend is the parallel between long\nshoremen and dockworkers\u2019 strikes\nnow occurring simultaneously on\nboth sides of the Atlantic. But these\nwildcat strikes are merely the un\ndisciplined fringe of a strike wave\nwhich threatens to spread as war\nplants close down or are reconverted\non a peacetime basis. Obviously,\nboth America and Britain are con\nfronted with a major problem in\nlabor-management relations which,\nunless constructively dealt with, can\nhave the gravest consequences.\nThe*way Britain handles the diffi\nculty will have special interest for\nus, because Britain now has a gov\nernment in which organized labor\nis the controlling factor. The British\nLabor Party is a composite political\norganization with an influential\nwing of radical \u201cintellectuals,\u201d while\nits recent sweeping victory at the\npolls was due largely to the votes of\nmiddle-class electors not formally\naffiliated with the party. Neverthe\nless, the party\u2019s core remains the\nclosely integrated bodies of organ\nized labor known as the T. U. C. or\nTrades Union Congress, which is\ntechnically distinct from the Labor\nparty though functioning with it in\nharmonious co-operation. The Brit\nish trades unions have a much\nlonger background than ours, with\na record of sane leadership and ef\nfective discipline over their member\nship which has facilitated stable\ncontractural relations with employ\ncia. n wuut\u00bbi suiae ate mat, oi rne\nBritish dockers is thus a much more\nserious phenomenon than its fellow\nhere. These strikers belong to the\nTransport and General Workers\u2019\nUnion, one of the most numerous\nand powerful British labor organiza\ntions. It should also be noted that\nthe mass demonstration of London\nconstruction workers unanimously\ndemanded the resignation of the\nexecutive head of their union. These\nevents appear to indicate a radical\nrevolt against existing leadership.\nFor Britain, a crippling wave of\nstrikes would be even more serious\nthan with us, because Britain\u2019s post\nwar economy is in desperate straits\nand needs speedy reconversion to\navert national catastrophe. Though\nthe government has not yet taken\npositive action, Minister of Labor\nGeorge Isaacs has virtually ordered\nthe striking dockers back to work,\nwarning them that a continuation\nof their unauthorized walkouts, now\nmore than a fortnight old, would\nJeopardize Britain\u2019s food supply, de\nlay demobilization of the armed\nforces, and work against the strikers\u2019\nown interests. Consideration of the\nlabor crisis will doubtless be prompt\nly taken up by Parliament which\nhas just reconvened.\nNow that the atom has been split\nsuccessfully, it may be possible for\nsome superscientist to accommo\ndate more people in Washington by\nsubdividing the typical Washington\napartment.\nA good idea for motorists these\ndays is to forget or ignore the num\nerals 40, 50, 60, etc., on their speed\nometers and, instead, constantly vis\nualize the word \u201ctires\u201d as replacing\nthose figures.\nOne of the prospective blessings of\npeace is the hope that average wom\nen will quit wearing slacks long\nenough to find out how horrible they\nlook even on pretty young girls.\nThe sweetest music in the world\nIs that of an honest-to-goodneas\nbeefsteak broiling.\n\nTimes Still Require\nA Sense of Urgency\nThe World Will Be a Dangerous\nPlace Until Peace Is Sure\nBy William H. Harrison.\nWhen it ends, war tends to become\na thing only dimly remembered. After\nthe shooting stops and people return to\ntheir normal pursuits of malting a living\nand seeking as much happiness as they\ncan find, the sense of urgency passes,\nthe \u201cfeel\" of danger fades away, the\nApocalyptic picture of the past\u2014which\nonce seemed so real, so close, so terrify\ning\u2014now grows hazy. Time is more\nthan a healer. It is a curtain of sorts,\na comforting mist, blurring or blotting\nout entirely the memory of events which\nmost men and women would just as\nsoon forget.\nIf time did not do this, of course, the\npast, with all its pain and terror, would\nremain as vivid as if it were still here,\nand the human spirit would be over\nwhelmed by it. To that extent, therefore,\npeople may count themselves lucky that\ntheir remembrance of some things be\ncomes weaker and weaker with the\nyears, but there is a great danger in this,\ntoo, because men and nations are now\nat the threshhold of an age in which\nthey will be literally Inviting their own\ndestruction if they carry their forget\nfulness too far or if they fall to realize\nhow electronics and atomic power have\nso changed the nature of war that the\nwhole world will be living in a kind of\nemergency until a permanent peace is\nassured.\nThis Is a matter of particular Im\nportance for the United States. Of all\nmajor powers, ours Is the most prone\nto stop thinking about war when war\nis over. Ever since the Revolution, the\nAmerican people have been like that.\nAfter every great conflict, we have put\naside our weapons to the point of\nneglecting them altogether. Relying on\nthe once-protective reaches of the oceans\naround us and letting our wishes govern\nour thoughts and action, we have\nexcelled the world in our capacity to\ndemobilize not only our armed power\nbut our minds as well. It is an old\nnational trait, and a highly honorable\none, but, unfortunately\u2014in this new era\nof the atomic bomb and the guided\nmissile of supersonic speed\u2014it is a trait\nthat can become the death of us if\ngiven free rein.\nAfter the tensions, the alarms, the\nfatigue, the savagery and the vast blood\nletting of the Second World War, it is\nonly natural that the Nation should now\nfind emotional release in demobilization.\nYet we can no longer take the risk\u2014as\nin the past\u2014of letting that demobiliza\ntion go so far as to leave the country\nphysically and mentally disarmed in a\nworld that will be exceedingly dangerous\nuntil a genuine peace is established. Our\nhighest military leaders may be striking\na distasteful note when they say it, but\nthey are right when they say that the\nUnited States, to insure its survival, 1\nmust now do three things, in addition\nto working unremittingly for inter-\nnational collective security: (1) Main\ntain land, sea and air power adequate\nto the times; (2) inaugurate compulsory j\npeacetime training, and (3\u00bb carry on\nconstant research and development in\nall fields of science.\nAt the moment the American people\nseem anything but disposed to favor\nsuch a program, and this raises the\nquestion whether the vast majority are\nfully aware\u2014or can be made to become\nfully aware\u2014of how truly dangerous\nthe world is. Is it properly realized, for\ninstance, that the oceans have lost\ntheir old defensive significance? Is\nit clear that if there is another war. 1\nit will be far more total than the one\njust ended? Is there sufficient public\nappreciation of the kind of gas and\nbacteriological weapons now at man's\ndisposal? Is there doubt about the\nmeaning of transoceanic rockets? Are\nthe potentialities of the age vivid\nenough to convince every one that if\nit is unprepared, this Nation, no less\nthan other nations, can be overwhelmed\novernight by a sudden attack in which\nsingle bombs\u2014about which long-term\nsecrecy is Impossible\u2014can virtually\nerase whole cities like Washington? In\nshort, does America in general under\nstand that its scientists and political\nj arid military leaders are speaking lit\ni erally when they make the seemingly\nfantastic statement that in the era\nimmediately ahead, It will be possible\n\u2014at least theoretically\u2014to destroy life\ncompletely not only in one or two\ncountries but all over the face of the\nearth?\n\nAlthough the implications of the age\nof electronics and atomic energy\u2019 are\nthus more appalling than anything\nthat has heretofore confronted man\nkind it is doubtful that the people as\na whole have yet come to a full ap\npreciation of the situation. Demobiliz\ning as fast as they can, forgetting the\nSecond World War as fast as they\ncan, they are understandably enjoy\ning their release from the recent sense\nof urgency and the \u201cfeel\" of danger,\nand in such a mood they can hardly\nbe expected to welcome the idea that\nthe times demand continued prepared\nness; they can hardly be expected to\ngive much thought to the fact that\nfor some years to come, until there\nis a guarantee that the peace will be\nlasting, there will be a kind of inter\nnational emergency.\nNevertheless that fact must be faced\nand the public must be made so aware\nof it that a year from now, or two or\nmore years from how, the security of\nthis Nation will in no way be neg\nlected. On two basic points the Amer\nican people must henceforth remain\nwide aw'ake and continue to feel a\nsense of urgency. The first of these\nis that we must have an adequate up\nto-the-minute military establishment\nalong the lines now being suggested\nby qualified authorities. The second\nis that since this will be a dreary\nworld if the different powers convert\nthemselves into armed camps eying each\nother in an atmosphere of mutual alarm\nand distrust, the United States must\nW\u2019ork untiringly\u2014despite all temporary\u2019\ndisappointments\u2014at the vital task of\nestablishing a world organization that\nwill really guarantee world peace.\nOnce such an organization is func\ntioning, a drastic general disarmament\nwill be possible. Meanwhile, peoples\neverywhere must come to understand\nthat man\u2019s new knowledge in the new\nage, though full of immense potential\ngood, can blast all civilization to pieces\nif misused. As never before in the\nhistory of the world, there must be\nenlightened public opinion on this score.\nAs never before, there must be an or\nganized effort by governments\u2014and\nperhaps by special private agencies as\n1\nOur Changing Religion\nBy the Rev. George M. Anderson,\nPastor of the Park View Christian Church.\nIt is a fact well known to thinking\npeople that a thing that ceases to\ngrow begins to die. Life is growth,\nwhen growth ceases decay sets in.\nNowhere has this been better evi\ndenced than in religion.\nModern religious thought appre\nciates that there is good in all re\nligion, that all religion is the striv\ning of man to achieve a better state,\nto improve himself and his fellow\nmen in their relation one to another.\nIt is a conscious seeking after the\nCreator and, springing from such\na source, cannot possibly be all bad.\nModern religious thought empha\nsizes the importance of toleration,\nwhich was certainly one of the cen\ntral themes of the teachings of\nthe Nazarene.\nLess and less stress Is beng laid\nupon creeds. The majority of mod\nern church members are ignorant of\nthe creed of their churches and\ncare very little about them. Many\ncannot tell the difference between\nthe creed of their own church and\nthat of a neighboring denomination.\nDenominatlonalism is dying, and any\nthing that will hasten the process\nwill hasten the coming of His King\ndom. More and more the churches\nare coming to realize that their\npurpose is to teach the lessons of\nJesus and not to emphasize distinc\ntons of creed which are not differ\nences. Co-operation between the\nchurches is becoming more and more\ncommon and it is also becoming\nIncreasingly essential if the church,\nespecially the country church, is to\nsurvive. There is a common end\nin view', the furtherance of the Lord\u2019s\nKingdom, and there is /io more\nexcuse for divided forces in the\nwar against evil than there would\nhave been in the war against the\nAxis. Amalgamation is certain to\nbe the eventual result. How soon\nthat comes depends upon the at\ntitudes of individuals as well as\ndenominations.\nModern religion teaches that it i>\nmore efficacious to educate a person\nto want to be good rather than to\nscare him into it by threat\u00ae of pun\nishment. The idea of punishment\nhas been more or less discarded be\ncause it is not consistent with the\nidea of a God of love. Sufficient evi\ndence has been produced in recent\nyears that it is impossible to legislate\ngoodness into the human race to\nwarrant religious teachers in seeking\nsome other method, and it is equally\ncertain that the methods being ap\nplied successfully in education of a\nsecular character should also apply\nto religious education.\nMoreover, modem religious thought,\nadopting other psychological ideas,\nappreciates that the punishment of\nevil seldom is postponed to a future\nlife but is exacted right here in this\nlife. Medical science is coming to\nrecognize the effects of such emotions\nas hate and fear on the body, even\ngoing so far as to attribute certain\ndiseases to those and other emotions,\nthus substantiating the assertion\nthat, in hating a person, in doing him\nevil, we are bringing certain inevit\nable results down upon our own\nbodies. As these ideas permeate reli\ngious thought, they are bound to\nshow in a more serious consideration\nfor the theory styled \u201cretribution\u201d by\nRalph Waldo Emerson in his essay\non \u201cCompensation.\u201d\n\nThe truly religious spirit finds God\nin every gracious flower, adores Him\nin every daybreak and sunset, hears\nHim with the poets in the vast unity\nof things. Wherever the true Chris\ntian is, there is God. Whatsoever\ntasks he undertakes for the general\ngood are part and parcel of the Divine\nwill. God's temple is the universe.\nCapital Sidelights\nBy Will P. Kennedy.\nRepresentative Edith N. Rogers of\nMassachusetts has put into the Con\ngressional Record an interesting story\non \u2022\u2018The Heroism of Betty Barton,\"\ndaughter of the late Representative\nBruce Barton. Miss Barton was para\nlyzed by a spinal injury in an auto\nmobile accident more than 10 years ago.\nLast year Miss Barton wrote a book\nentitled \"Now I Live Again,\" telling how\nout of anguish and discouragement her\nown conquering spirit achieved such\nphysical improvement that she now\ngoes about alone in New York, as Mrs.\nRogers says, \"emancipated from sym\npathy, and an object lesson of coura\ngeous hope to hundreds of tragic war\nvictims.\u201d\n\n\nWorld War II emphasized to many\nin Congress how the start they gave\nto young men through appointment to\nAnnapolis or West Point has resulted\nIn real service to the Nation. During\nWorld War I Representative John Q.\nTilson of Connecticut, later House\nleader in the Sixty-ninth, Seventieth\nand Seventy-first Congresses, made a\nseries of speeches on armament. He\nhad been an officer in the Spanish\nAmerican War. At the same time the\nchief janitor at the Capitol was Charles\nKaschub of Meriden, Conn., who per\nsuaded Mr. Tilson to give an appoint\nment to Annapolis to a boy in whom\nhe was interested\u2014George A. Lange.\nMr. Kaschub subsequently was a Senate\ndoorkeeper and employed at the Ar\nlington Hotel and City Club, and now\nwith his eyesight practically gone he\nis living at the Masonic and Eastern\nStar Home Proudly visiting the Capitol\nthe other day, he boasted about his\nappointee to Annapolis. George Lange\nnow has been in the Navy 21 years. He\nis a commander and was stationed for\na time at the White House, accompany\ning President Roosevelt on various\ntrips. The President had him appointed\nexecutive officer on the U. S. S. Co\nlumbia, a light cruiser, commissioned\nJuly 29, 1942.\nMr. Kaschub has just received a let\nter from his protege, recounting the\nwar service of that ship as follows:\nOfficially credited with the destruction\nof 27 planes, assisted in sinking 1\ncruiser and 1 destroyer at the battle of\nEknpress Augusta Bay and 2 battle\nships, 1 cruiser and 1 destroyer at the\nbattle of Surigao Straits, participation\nin nine shore bombardments, com\nmended by Secretary Forrestal \"for\noutstanding heroism in action,\u201d with\nthe entire personnel authorized to wear\nthe Navy Unit Commendation Ribbon;\nin nine officially designated operations\nand engagements for which Bronze\nStars have been authorized.\n\nRepresentative Charles L. Gifford of\nMassachusetts, now in his 74th year,\nhaving been a school teacher, real estate\ndealer, oyster and cranberry grower,\nmember of both branches of the State\nLegislature and 23 years a member of\nCongress, is starting all over again on\nhis lifetime hobby of making scrap\nbooks. One year ago his extraordinary\ncollection of many scrapbooks on a\nscore of subjects on which he has\nworked steadily for well over half a\ncentury was wiped out in a Cape Cod\ncyclone\u2014together with his beautiful\nhome and office, his treasured century\nold violin and priceless family heirlooms\n\u2014all but the sturdy stone chimney,\naround which he has rebuilt a smaller\nhome. But Mr. Gifford had his heart\nset on leaving his collection of scrap\nbooks to his two grandsons, and so with\nstubborn persistency he is starting to\nbuild up another collection, endeavoring\nas far as he can to get duplicates of\nphotostats of various items which he\nparticularly prized in the volumes he\nlost. Scores of friends who had seen\nand admired his scrapbooks are helping\nhim in his search for duplicates. About\n10 of the destroyed books contained\nclippings which were the best biography\nof his life. Many of these are being\nreplaced by his friends, with supple\nmental comments which are going Into\nnew volumes.\nI\nThe Old Bait\nFrom the Victoria Times.\nThe greatest danger to liberty is man's\nwillingness to accept a master if he calls\nhimself a friend of the poor and of free\ndom.\nwell\u2014to make it abundantly clear that\nthe human race, if it goes to war again,\nwill be perfectly capable pf, destroying\nitself.\nFifty Years Ago\nThe Star for October 5, 1895, reported\nthat: \"The corpse of the biggest man j\nthat ever lived has\nGigantic Mummy been dug up near\nFound San Diego, Calif.\nAt all events, there j\nIs no satisfactory record in ancient or\nmodern history of any human being i\nnearly so tall. The mummy\u2014for in such\na condition the remains were found\u2014is\nthat of a person who must have been\nabout 9 feet high in life. This makes\nallowance for a shrinkage which may\nbe pretty closely calculated. The cadaver\nhas been carefully inspected and meas\nured by Prof. Thomas Wilson, curator\nof the department of prehistoric anthro\npology In the Smithsonian Institution j\nand other scientists. The tape line even i\nI now registers the length from heel to j\n1 top of head at 8 feet 4 inches.\u201d In the\nlanguage of \"Yankee Doodle,\u201d the giant 1\nwas \"as big as all out doors; some\nthought him much the larger.\u201d\n\nAn editorial in The Star of October\n7, 1895, argued that: \u201cIf it be true, as\nstated, that Gen.\nFreedom for Harrison is earning\nEx-Presidents le\u00abal fees that n\u00abt\nhim an income two\nor three times as large as that which j\nthe country paid him while he occupied j\nthe White House, there would seem to\nhave been found an answer to the\nmuch-discussed question: \"What shall\nbe done with our ex-Presidents?\u2019 The\nbest possible thing to do, it would ap\npear. is to let them severely alone.\nLet them remain as they are, good, use\nful, prosperous citizens, honored in their\ncommunities and in their profession.\u201d\n\nreesiaences ior rne widows or c-niei\nExecutive* also, seemingly, were a mat\nter of public interest\nNew Home for half a century ago,\nMrs. Gront since The Star *or\nOctober 8, 1895. told\nat considerable length how: \"Mrs. Grant\nhas purchased the Edmunds house on\nMassachusetts avenue\" and \"after a\nshort visit in New York will have i\nall her household belongings brought\non from that city.\u201d Her daughter, Mrs.\nSartoris, it was explained, would make\nher home with her \"for the present at\nleast.\u201d Miss Rose Marie Sartoris was in\nschool at Georgetown Convent and Al\ngernon Sartoris likewise was here and\nprobably would remain \"as the love of\nthis country and its institutions is his\nstrong characteristic.\u201d\n\nOnly 30 years had passed since the\nend of the War Between the States\nwhen The Star of Oc\nLongstreet in tober 9, 1895, an\nWashington nounced that: \"Ar\nrangements have been\ncompleted by members of the Confed\nerate Veterans' Association to give an\ninformal reception this evening at\nOrme's Hall, southeast corner of E and\nEleventh streets N.W., to Gen. James\nLongstreet, who is visiting the city and\nsojourning at 1534 I street N.W.\u201d The\nConfederate leader thus to be honored\nwas the last surviving lieutenant gen\neral who had served under the Start\nand Bars. It was stipulated in the ad\nvance publicity that the walls of the\nassembly room \"will be hung with many\npictures, relics and decorations pertain\ning to the Southern cause,\u201d also that:\n\u201cAn orchertra will be present, and after\n10 o\u2019clock dancing wjj]l be in order.\u201d\nThe Star for October 10,1895, discussed\nat length the first performance of \"The\nHeart of Maryland\"\nMr. Belas^o's on any stage. It\nLatest Success had been Presented\nunder the personal\nsupervision of David Belasco at the\ni Grand Opera House the previous eve\nning. \"The scenery,\u201d It was contended,\n\"is beyond description.\" In the cast\nwere: Mrs. Leslie Carter, whose \u201cperson\nality dominates the entire production\";\nMaurice Barrymore, who was \u201cjust as\neasy and graceful and strong as ever\u201d;\nJohh E. Kellerd, who was \u201can ideal\nvillain\u201d; Frank Mordaunt, who \u201chad a\ndifficult role and one to which he gave\na distinct value\u201d; Mias Georgia\nBusby, Miss Angela Macaull, John W.\nJennings and Henry Weaver, Jr. The\nplay, The Star critic suggested, \u201cwill\nsurely net\u201d Mr. Belasco \u201cboth revenue\nand reputation.\u201d\n\nAdvertising \u201ccopy\u201d half a century back\nas a general rule was not very colorful,\nbut there were excep\nLivery Stable tions. For example, The\nDe Luxe star ot October 11> 1895>\ncontained a notice\nwhich read: \u201cDo you own a line horse or\na handsome \u2018pair\u2019? If so, you doubtless\nI\nSweden's Economic\nStatus Is Favorable\nObserver, However, Doubts That\nSocialism Is Responsible\nBy Raymond Moley.\nSwedish leaders already are boasting,\nperhaps too much, that, in her good\nfortune, Sweden is \"in the same boat as\nAmerica.\u201d This comment is made by\nher Secretary of Commerce, a Socialist\nand an economist, Prof. Gunnar Myrdal.\nThe professor-politician is well known\nto many American businessmen.\nProf. Myrdal is in a position where\nhe is largely responsible for the foreign\nand domestic economic policies of his\ncountry, now governed by a laborite ma\njority. He explains that Sweden, in\navoiding a postwar depression, will\npartly use the same methods as the\nUnited States. Of course, we all wish\nthat our plans, which seem so clear to\nProf. Myrdal, were a trifle clearer to us.\nAnd we hope that Sweden will not be\nlieve that our present wave of strikes\nis part of our plan for recovery.\nThe economic situation of Sweden,\nindeed, is bright. It gave or pledged\nto neighbors during the war, partly as\ngifts and partly as loans, no less than\n$675,000,000. Translated into American\nper capita terms this Is about half what\nwe lend-leased to Britain. Of these\nloans, Sweden already has canceled\n$12,500,000 to Denmark and $135,000,000\nto Norway. It is very doubtful whether\nSweden ever will get back the $55,000,000\ngiven to Finland.\nWhether Sweden was spared the rav\nages of war by accident or design is\nnot clear. It is claimed that Hermann\nGoering, in loving appreciation of the\nexcellence of the lunatic asylums where\nhe rebuilt his shattered nerves in the\n1920s, interceded with Hitler to spare\nSweden. A better explanation is the\nfact that Sweden was a goose that laid\nsteel eggs for Hitler\u2019s war machine. The\nNazis preferred the eggs to the goose.\nIn any event, Sweden did a thriving\nbusiness with all concerned and her out\nlook now is marred only by a few em\nbarrassing connections between some of\nher people and German industrial con\nIn Prof. Myrdal\u2019s program, he says\nvery little about more nationalizations\nor socializations. His whole concern is\nto increase Sweden's exports. His plans\nfor stabilizing Swedish economy are:\n1. To provide low interest rates for\nIndustrial needs;\n2. To stimulate housing construction;\n3. To use public money as a stabilizer\nof business cycles, as, for example, in\nthe electrification of railroads;\n4. To subsidize consumer purchases of\ndurable goods, such as furniture, \u2018\u2018some\nwhat along the lines of the American\nfood-stamp plan\u201d;\n5. To stockpile \u201ceverything that can\nbe stockpiled without destroying th\u00ab\nmarket.\u201d\nThis stockpile idea is somewhat like an\nAmerican proposal known as the \u201ccon\nsumer subscribing plan\u201d advocated bv\nDr. John Pierson. It seems to have\nattracted little support here.\nMost interesting to Americans is the\nargument of Prof. Myrdal that Sweden\nwill find it much easier to combat infla\ntion than will the United States, be\ncause public\u2014that is, \u201csocialized\u201d enter\nprise\u2014is relatively larger in Sweden.\nThe Swedish state has taken over the\nrailroad, telephone, telegraph and other\nenterprises. It also practically controls\nhousing through having taken over most\nof the financing involved. Another dif\nference pointed out by Prof. Myrdal is\nthat there is in Sweden \u201cvery close col\nlaboration between government and pri\nvate capital as to investment in indus\ntry.\u201d\nIt is a shame to question the en\nthusiasm of a Socialist over the benefits\nof a socialized economy. But it cannot\nbe too strongly urged that whatever tha\nform of Sweden's economy might have\nbeen, prosperity would have resulted\nfrom her fortunate exclusion from the\nravages of war. Socialism, of itself, did\nnot make her be spared. Other coun\ntries, with similar state-owned indus\ntries, went down before the tide. It\nwas the fortunate possession of the\nmeans needed by Germany and, more\nrecently, by Russia, which has helped\nSweden emerge in such good shape.\nIt must also be added that Prof.\nMyrdal neglects to point out the essential\nmildness of Sweden's socialism. Swed\nish, as well as British trade union\npolicy, does not trend toward dictator\nship or total nationalization. The Myr\ndal program is considerably less radical\nthan the restraints and government\ncompetition suggested by the prewar\nNew Deal. The private profit system is\nstill a very important element in Swedish\neconomy. Any one who doubts that\nneed only seek the instruction provided\nby a few commercial transactions with\nshrewd Swedish private concerns.\nEarly Newspapers\nrrern the Manchester Guardian.\nThe British Museum newspaper library\nat Colindale, which received a direct hit\nfrom a high-explosive bomb on October\n20, 1940, has been unable to check its\nlosses owing to lack of space. All the\nnewspapers that were saved were cram\nmed into a room already full, and there\nthey must remain unsorted until new\npremises for the library can be found.\nIt is thought the losses included some\nof the earliest newspapers in the col\nlection. dating from the 18th and 19th\ncenturies, many of which, it is feared,\ncannot be replaced.\nA few offers of old newspapers have\nalready been made to the library, but\nit will be difficult to attempt replace\nment before the exact losses can be as\ncertained.\nwant them to have all the comforts and\ncare that a modern\u2014properly ventilated\n\u2014thoroughly drained\u2014amply lighted\nestablishment\u2014such as ours\u2014affords.\nThere\u2019s still room for a few more board\ners. We make a special of hiring \u2018swell*\nturnouts by the trip, day, week or month.\nReasonable rates. Downey\u2019s Hotel for\nHorses, 1622-1628 L street N.W.\u201d\nv v\nThe Star for October 12, 1895, gave\nfront page space to an article in which\nthe question of \"Who\nNew Bishop of will be elected bishop\nWashington \u201cew ^oces#\nof Washington?\u2019 waa\ndebated. \u201cSpeculation as to the person\nality of the coming bishop takes a wide\nrange,\" it was asserted, because \"under\nthe conditions as they exist at present,\nit is a matter of absolute impossibility\nto predict not only who the man will be\nbut even the probabilities in the case.\"\nThe name of the Rev. Dr. Randolph H.\nMcKim, rector of the Church of the\nEpiphany, was mentioned as that of\n\u201cthe most probable candidate for the\nnew office,\u201d but The Star suggested thaj\nhis election was \u201cnot a certainty\u201d\u2014and\nThe Star waa right.","height":"31792","width":"22584"}}
